VMORE SEATS IN THE AIR -- Domestic airline capacity rose significantly in May, and with all the extra seats in the skies, some carriers were unable to keep their planes as full as they had been in May 2003. JetBlue Airways reported one of the biggest increases in capacity: a 43.5 percent gain compared with May 2003. But JetBlue's load factor, the percentage of available seats sold, dropped 3.1 percentage points, to 81.8 percent. American Airlines' capacity was up 9.7 percent; its load factor dropped 0.5 percentage points, to 73.1 percent. At Delta Air Lines, capacity rose 19.1 percent, but the load factor fell 0.4 point, to 73.9 percent. Continental Airlines increased capacity by 13.8 percent; load factor fell 1.2 points, to 74.7 percent. UAL's United Airlines said its capacity rose 17.2 percent over May 2003, with a rise of 2.9 points in load factor, to 80.1 percent. Northwest Airlines reported an 8.4 percent increase in capacity and a gain of 5.37 points in load factor, to 80.7 percent. At US Airways, capacity was up 4.9 percent, and load factor increased 1.9 percentage points, to 75.4 percent. Southwest Airlines reported a 4.8 percent jump in capacity, and a rise of 4.6 points in load factor, to 73.9 percent.
