aVLOST IN AMERICA -- In some cities, getting lost is a cinch. About two-thirds of business travelers who rent cars say they expect to get lost while driving in certain cities, according to a survey commissioned by Avis Rent a Car and Motorola, which makes software for Avis Assist, a navigation system that provides driving directions on cellphones. The 10 urban areas most difficult to navigate, according to the study by Bert Sperling, the author of BestPlaces guides in print and online: Boston; Washington; San Francisco; Baltimore; New York-Northern New Jersey; Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood-Pompano Beach, Fla.; Los Angeles; Seattle-Everett, Wash.; Providence, R.I.-Pawtucket, Mass.; and Norfolk-Newport News-Virginia Beach, Va. FRILLS ADDED -- Discount airlines used to brag about their no-frills service, while major airlines countered that business travelers wanted more than a cheap, uncomfortable seat. But some discount carriers -- which have been adding long-haul domestic flights on routes that were once the exclusive province of the majors -- are starting to stress premium-class service. ATA Airlines said it would begin offering discounted business-class service in late November after reconfiguring its fleet of Boeing 737's and 757's, installing a business-class section with 12 seats each. AirTran Airways has been promoting $35 space-available upgrades to business class, which provides 15 percent of its revenue. Last month, AirTran said it had placed 50 orders for Boeing 737-700's and 737-800's as it geared up to battle for market share on longer-haul routes.
