VWHEN Pan American World Airways is reborn tomorrow, with a daily nonstop between New York's Kennedy International Airport and Miami, and between Kennedy and Los Angeles, passengers can enroll in an unusual frequent-flier plan, named World Pass. Economy passengers on the two-class carrier will receive one and one-quarter frequent-flier miles for each actual air mile flown, rather than the usual one mile, while first-class passengers will receive one and three-quarter miles. In addition, all passengers will receive 1,000 miles as an enrollment bonus. Members can earn a free flight after 20,000 miles, rather than the more common 25,000, while elite status -- with priority check-in privileges -- will kick in at 15,000 miles, instead of 25,000.
