aVIn late afternoon, as most people are heading home from work, a large, unmarked room on an upper floor at PNC Bank is just starting to buzz with activity. Among the rows of women in cubicles is Caren Good, 34, tall, thin and stylishly groomed. New to the job, she carefully slips checks into a whirring machine with her left hand, while her right records the amounts on a keyboard. Her evening's work will show up later as thousands of entries on bank statements wrapped around packets of canceled checks. For this she earns $7.10 an hour, her highest wage in years. Ms. Good, whose schooling ended with high school graduation in 1981 and whose working years have been spent mostly in short-lived clerical jobs or occasional gigs as a poorly paid model, is among the millions of Americans whose earnings have seldom ranged far above the minimum wage, now $4.75 a hour. Caught up in forces that have made incomes increasingly unequal, people at the bottom of the wage scale like Ms. Good have slipped farther behind nearly every year for more than two decades.
