VOH YEAH? SEZ WHO? -- New York City is ranked the most polite of major world cities in a survey in the July issue of Reader's Digest. The magazine sent reporters to major cities in 35 countries to study public courtesy. After New York in the top five were Zurich, Toronto, Berlin and São Paulo. The bottom five were Singapore, Seoul, Kuala Lumpur, Bucharest and Mumbai. FEWER EUROPEANS COMING -- European air passenger traffic to the United States was off more than 9 percent in the first quarter of this year, says Donald N. Martin & Company, citing Commerce Department data. No reasons were suggested for the downturn, after increases of 6.5 percent and 12.1 percent in 2005 and 2004, respectively. One possible benefit, the forecaster says, is that ''more seats may be available for Americans bound for Europe'' this summer, though trans-Atlantic fares are projected to remain high. U.S. SHARE OF WORLD TRAVEL OFF -- In a speech to the Foreign Policy Association last week J. W. Marriott Jr., chairman of Marriott International, noted that while the global travel industry has grown about 30 percent in the last decade, the United States' share of world travel has shrunk by as much as 9 percent. A major reason is that security procedures for obtaining visas abroad are increasingly tangled. The average wait in Brazil for an interview to obtain a visa to visit the United States is 55 days, he said. In 2000, about 737,000 Brazilians traveled to the United States. Last year, only 485,000 came, he said. MAXJET GROWS -- MaxJet, the discount all-business-class start-up that flies between Stansted Airport serving London and New York and Washington, acquired its third 767 aircraft. In May, the carrier reported a load factor -- the average number of seats occupied by paying customers -- of 72 percent on the New York-London route. Gary Rogliano, the chief executive, said MaxJet planned to acquire a fourth 767 and to announce a new domestic city flying to Stansted later this year. He declined to identify the city. ET CETERA -- Marriott Hotels and Renaissance Hotels are rolling out lobby computer stations to allow guests to check in for flights and print out their boarding passes. Ten hotels -- all properties of Marriott International -- now have the stations and 150 more will be equipped within two weeks, Marriott said. Virgin Air reported a 10.1 percent increase in business-class traffic for the fiscal year ended Feb. 28, citing increasing demand for the new Upper Class Suite business-class product it introduced in late 2003 Underscoring rising fares, the Air Transport Association said that yields -- prices paid per mile flown -- for domestic airlines rose 11.9 percent in May compared with May 2005. JOE SHARKEY
