VMarriott International Inc. posted a loss in its fourth quarter as business and leisure travel fell and the company wrote down the value of property and loans. The loss of $116 million, or 48 cents a share, is in contrast to net income of $149 million, or 59 cents a share, a year earlier. Marriott, which is based in Bethesda, Md., said its revenue fell 10 percent, to $2.87 billion. Marriott took $85 million in write-downs of off-balance-sheet loans it guaranteed or made to developers. Arne Sorenson, the chief financial officer, said that no more write-downs were expected. The company had $1.15 billion in off-balance-sheet items representing loans and guarantees to hotel developers as of the end of the year. The company's revenue per available room, a measure of average occupancy and room rate, fell 25 percent in the quarter from a year earlier, compared with the company's estimate of a decline of as much as 35 percent.
