VAlthough he turned 70 last month, J. W. Marriott Jr., chairman and chief executive of Marriott International, still flies 130,000 miles annually and visits 200 of his 2,500 hotels. On a quick inspection of the Marriott Marquis in Manhattan last week, he criticized the bedspreads, lighting and color schemes in several guest rooms but proudly pointed out the clean grout in a bathroom. He inspected sauces in the hotel's kitchen to make sure they were fresh and told a worker to throw out a canceled order of chicken.
p700
aV''We're not hoteliers,'' said Christopher M. Jeffries, a founding partner of Millennium Partners. It seems a peculiar claim for a developer who is building eight hotels across the country, including a new Ritz-Carlton in this city, which has long been synonymous with that hyphenated name. But a bed check bears him out. While there are 193 transient rooms at the six-month-old, $500 million Ritz-Carlton Hotel and Towers, a pair of angular high-rise bookends on the Boston Common, there are 304 condominium apartments. Priced around $900 a square foot, they use Ritz-Carlton services and trade on its reputation and lion's head logo. Half have been sold.
