VNEW ORLEANS REVIVAL -- As New Orleans stirs back to life commercially, Marriott International said yesterday that 12 of its hotels in the city were now accepting reservations for arrivals starting Nov. 1. They include the JW Marriott, the New Orleans Marriott and the New Orleans Marriott at the Convention Center, and four Courtyard and two Residence Inn hotels. Five other Marriott hotels in the New Orleans area, including the two Ritz-Carlton hotels, will remain temporarily closed to the public until further notice, the company said. BUSINESS JETS BACK AT REAGAN -- Corporate jet service is returning to Reagan Washington National Airport today after being banned since the 2001 terrorist attacks because of the airport's proximity to the White House and the Capitol. Two private jets are scheduled to land today at the airport, which has been allocated 48 slots daily for arrivals and departures. ''We finally got all the pieces in place,'' said Dan Kidder, a spokesman for the National Air Transport Association. That trade group's president, James K. Coyne, is scheduled to be among the passengers on the inaugural flight, a charter operated by New World Jet from the terminal operated by Jet Aviation at Teterboro Airport in New Jersey. Teterboro is one of 12 airports approved by federal authorities for originating private flights to Reagan, which handled an average of 122 charter and private flights daily before the terrorist attacks. The new security requirements for Reagan service include a rule that a law enforcement officer be on board each flight. PREVENTIVE MEDICINE -- Plan ahead for possible influenza outbreaks, just in case, the National Business Travel Association says. The association, the trade group for corporate travel managers, said yesterday that it was working with Dr. R. Bradley Sack, an authority on infectious diseases, to help companies prepare for a possible outbreak of avian flu. Flu viruses can be readily transported around the world by air travel. Dr. Sack, the director of travel medicine services for Johns Hopkins University, will record a seminar on avian flu that will be available to members of the group on its Web site, www.nbta.org. ''Travel managers have a unique role as the key source of travel-related information for their companies and for business travelers,'' said Suzanne Fletcher, the trade group's president. BUSINESS-CLASS FARES CUT -- If you book at least seven days in advance, flying business class to London on British Airways just got cheaper -- about 20 percent less expensive than walk-up prices -- on some trans-Atlantic routes. Sample round-trip sale fares for British Air's Club World service are Kennedy to London, $6,967; Chicago O'Hare to London, $6,750; Los Angeles International to London, $8,887. MORE MILES -- Those airline mileage promotions just keep coming. Continental Airlines said yesterday that members of its OnePass frequent-flier program will get 500 bonus miles each time they fly on tickets purchased on its Web site www.continental.com. They also get 500 bonus miles for checking in online. JOE SHARKEY
